                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>Yet while we must accept this fate, we also must continue our obligation as engaged citizens to hold the government and their actions accountable going forward.  Donald Trump is not our newly elected dictator, he might make laws I don't like, (or just attempt to obliterate contraceptive rights and environmental protections entirely), but "<a href="http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/an-american-tragedy-2">the law is no protection</a>" and "whether they are carried out...depends on the general temper in the country."  </p>
<p>I have to trust Orwell's sentiment in "<a href="http://orwell.ru/library/articles/park/english/e_fpark">Freedom of the Park</a>," that we have the power for change, within the electorate and citizens' response to Trump's policies going forward, by educating them on these issues, if I want the possibility of a hopeful future.&nbsp;</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;"><em>Sheridan Wilbur is a Trinity sophomore.</em></p>
